body:
The following used to compile, with the assignment to the implicit variables `bar` and `foo` working properly:
```systemverilog
module FunctionReturnFailure(input bit u, output bit v);
  assign v = bar(u);
  function automatic bit bar(input bit b);
    bar = foo(b);
  endfunction
  function automatic bit foo(input bit a);
    foo = a;
  endfunction
endmodule
```
Running this through `circt-verilog` now produces the following error which looks like it's coming from how captured variables are treated:
```
broken.sv:3:26: error: expected captured value to be a ref-like type
  function automatic bit bar(input bit b);
                         ^
broken.sv:3:26: note: see current operation:
"func.func"() <{function_type = (!moore.i1) -> !moore.i1, sym_name = "bar", sym_visibility = "private"}> ({
^bb0(%arg0: !moore.i1):
  %0 = "moore.variable"(%arg0) : (!moore.i1) -> !moore.ref<i1>
  %1 = "moore.variable"() : () -> !moore.ref<i1>
  %2 = "moore.read"(%0) : (!moore.ref<i1>) -> !moore.i1
  %3 = "func.call"(%2) <{callee = @foo}> : (!moore.i1) -> !moore.i1
  "moore.blocking_assign"(%1, %3) : (!moore.ref<i1>, !moore.i1) -> ()
}) : () -> ()
```
@Scheremo Any idea what's going on here? Could this be the lvalue callback not realizing that there is an implicit `bar`/`foo` variable in scope?

